{{Unreferenced|date=June 2007}}'''''Lex rei sitae''''' is a legal doctrine of [[property law]] and of [[International private law]]. It is [[Latin]] for "the law where the property is situated". The law governing the transfer of title to property is dependent upon, and varies with, the ''lex rei sitae''. {{Italic title}}
LEX REI SITAE: "...real estate or immovable property is exclusively subject to the laws of the government within whose territory it is situated.".<ref>''Peet v. Peet,'' 229 Ill.341, 348-349, 82 N.E.376, 378; 1907 Ill. LEXIS 3126, 0</ref><ref>US Legal.Com - Lex Rei Sitae Law and Legal Definition</ref>
